{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: the core failure is misclassification of explicit imagery, which appears at the model judgment boundary, not just local logic. REAL-INFRA/LLM-DEP: correctness depends on real vision-model output content; a stubbed classifier would hide failures, so Agentic is required. Adversarial critique: if this were only testing routing of a pre-labeled 'flagged' result, Integration would suffice; but behavior text explicitly requires detecting explicit content. TOP2-CONTRAST runner-up Integration loses because it cannot validate actual explicit-content recognition. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow rejected because behavior does not require multiple agentic decisions in sequence, only one model decision plus deterministic hold/publish logic.","test_description":"Run moderation with the real vision model on a curated explicit-image set and assert each item is marked flagged, persisted in held-for-review state, and never reaches published state.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.74,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure is in semantic robustness to obfuscation, which is model-behavior quality, not parser wiring. LLM-DEP: outcomes vary with real text-model behavior; deterministic mocks will always miss true robustness failures. Adversarial critique: if scope were only normalization code (e.g., unicode folding) Unit/Integration could work, but behavior text requires end moderation flagging despite obfuscation. TOP2-CONTRAST runner-up Integration loses because stubs cannot expose real model blind spots on obfuscated hate speech. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow rejected because this behavior is one agentic classification decision, not a multi-agentic pipeline objective.","test_description":"Submit a suite of hate-speech variants with substitutions/lookalikes to the real text moderation model through the service and assert each is flagged and held.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.81,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: this is a module-handoff/orchestration failure (image result + text result + publish state transition), so Unit is too low. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) no required real OS/network/subprocess evidence in behavior text, (b) no dependence on model output quality beyond pass/pass fixtures, (c) no required multi-agentic judgment objective, (d) handoff correctness can be validated with deterministic pass responses. Adversarial critique: could be Agentic if 'passes checks' meant validating true model judgment quality, but text focuses on final publish vs hold/drop state transition. TOP2-CONTRAST runner-up Agentic loses because behavior does not ask whether models judge correctly, only whether system handles pass outcomes correctly. REJECTION-GATE: higher levels rejected by concrete text: 'passes both content checks' disqualifies needing real model-content evaluation.","test_description":"Wire service, datastore, and publish path with deterministic classifier doubles returning PASS for both checks; assert post is persisted as published and absent from hold queue, with no dropped-message path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Lower than System/Agentic because the assertion target is state orchestration after known pass outcomes, not infra timing or model quality.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full moderation pipeline — image check, text check, publish decision — completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"REAL-INFRA + MULTI-STEP: this is an end-to-end SLA over sequential stages including two real AI model calls and final decisioning; single-step tests miss composition latency. MOCK-HIDE: mocked models/network would systematically underreport tail latency and hide real deadline failures. Adversarial critique: if this were only measuring internal queue/dispatcher overhead with fixed local stubs, System could suffice; behavior text explicitly scopes the full pipeline including both checks. TOP2-CONTRAST runner-up Agentic loses because one model call timing is insufficient; requirement is chained image+text+decision completion under one deadline. REJECTION-GATE: no concrete text disqualifies higher Workflow; behavior explicitly names full sequence.","test_description":"Execute end-to-end submissions through production-like deployment path using real vision and text model calls; measure submit-to-decision latency and assert p95 (or required threshold metric) stays under 5 seconds.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.62}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: unavailability is typically surfaced through real HTTP/network failure modes (timeouts, 5xx, connection errors) that in-process fakes often simplify incorrectly. MOCK-HIDE: a naive mock exception can miss contract/parsing/timeout handling bugs that cause unintended auto-approval. Adversarial critique: Integration might be enough if adapter error contract is fully controlled and identical to real provider behavior, but behavior text gives no such guarantee. TOP2-CONTRAST runner-up Integration loses because real outage semantics are the failure boundary here. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic rejected by text because correctness does not depend on model output content, only failure-path handling when model is unavailable.","test_description":"Induce real vision-service unavailability in a system environment (e.g., block endpoint or force real 5xx/timeout) and assert image submissions enter retry queue with no publish/auto-approve transition.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.61,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: this behavior directly targets model decision consistency on borderline content; deterministic stubs cannot reveal variance. MOCK-MISS: failure is non-deterministic model output drift (or instability under repeated calls), not just local caching code. Adversarial critique: Integration could apply if requirement were only cache-key reuse guaranteeing same stored decision; but behavior text frames consistency of moderation decision itself for borderline inputs. TOP2-CONTRAST runner-up Workflow loses because this is repeated single-step model judgment, not multi-stage agentic handoff logic. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected because infrastructure realism alone cannot validate decision consistency without real model behavior.","test_description":"Submit the same borderline image repeatedly within the target time window using the real vision model path; assert decision variance rate stays within policy threshold and resulting hold/publish state is stable per policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.11,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.7